<p><b>Excerpt:</b> If your device is not receiving parameters from a DHCP server, it means the network interface will not be configured and consequently may not be able to connect to the network. This issue typically stems from a few common problems.</p>
<p><b>Probable Causes:</b></p>
<ul>
<li><b>LAN Connection Issues:</b> The physical LAN cable connection might not be working or could be incorrectly connected.</li>
<li><b>DHCP Server Inactivity:</b> The DHCP server itself might not be activated or running. A DHCP server is crucial for automatically supplying network devices with IP addresses and other configuration details.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Recommended Actions:</b></p>
<ol>
<li><b>Check LAN Cable:</b> Ensure that the LAN cable is functioning correctly and is securely connected to your device and the network.</li>
<li><b>Verify DHCP Server Status:</b> Confirm that the DHCP server is activated and operating as expected. Without an active DHCP server, your device cannot automatically obtain an IP address.</li>
<li><b>Manual IP Configuration:</b> As a temporary solution or if DHCP is not available, you can set the LAN IP address manually on your device.</li>
</ol>
<p>A DHCP client communicates over UDP port 68 to receive configuration, while the DHCP server listens on UDP port 67.</p>
