 space, specifically the X, Y, and Z coordinates. It has the following components:\\n    *   `x`: Data type `num` (X-value of the position).\\n    *   `y`: Data type `num` (Y-value of the position).\\n    *   `z`: Data type `num` (Z-value of the position).\\n    This data type is used for positions without orientation, whereas `robtarget` is used for robot positions including tool orientation and axis configuration.\\n*   **`restartdata`**: Stores restart information for trigger signals, often containing boolean values and numerical values (`dionum`, `num`) for pre and post conditions of various events.\\n*   **`tasks`**: Used to specify multiple RAPID program tasks. It has a `taskname` component, which is of data type `string`, to hold the name of a program task.\\n*   **`dionum`**: An alias data type for `num` (numerical value), often used for digital I/O operations. Predefined constants like `low` (0), `high` (1), and `edge` (2) are associated with `dionum` in the `base.sys` system module.\\n*   **`exec_level`**: An alias for `num` that specifies the program\'s execution level (e.g., `LEVEL_NORMAL`, `LEVEL_TRAP`, `LEVEL_SERVICE`).\\n*   **`triggdata`**: Stores information about positioning events during robot movements, used by instructions like `TriggL`, `TriggC`, or `TriggJ`.\\n*   **`identno`**: An alias data type for `num` used as an identity for move instructions in MultiMove coordinated robot systems.\\n*   **System Data Types**: Other data types like `errnum` (for error numbers) and `intnum` (for interrupt numbers) are part of the system data and mirror current RAPID system settings.\\n\\nThese structures and descriptions provide a consistent framework for understanding and utilizing the diverse range of data types available in the RAPID programming language.",\n    "Page Number": "",\n    "URL": "projects/338431745290/locations/global/collections/default_collection/dataStores/linamar-vector-bootcamp/branches/0/documents/abb-technical-reference-manual-p15"\n  },\n  {\n    "Document... <truncated>
