<p>A robot failing to move in a straight line can stem from a variety of underlying issues, broadly categorized into mechanical, electrical, and software problems.</p>
<h3>Mechanical Issues</h3>
<p>Mechanical problems are a common cause of deviation from a straight path. These can include:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Calibration Errors:</strong> For industrial arms, incorrect robot calibration or an improperly defined Tool Center Point (TCP) can lead to inconsistent path accuracy. Similarly, for any robot, inaccurate sensor or actuator calibration will hinder straight movement. Recalibrating the robot axes and ensuring the tool and work object are correctly defined are recommended steps.</li>
<li><strong>Worn or Damaged Components:</strong>
<ul>
<li><strong>Bearings and Gearboxes:</strong> Worn or damaged bearings and gearboxes can introduce play and inconsistency in movement. This might be accompanied by noises like scraping, grinding, or clicking.</li>
<li><strong>Mechanical Joints:</strong> Damage to mechanical joints between a motor and gearbox, or to parallel bars in specific robot designs, can also cause path inaccuracies. Replacing faulty components is often necessary.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Brake Malfunctions:</strong> Issues with robot brakes not releasing correctly can impede movement and affect path accuracy.</li>
<li><strong>Loose Connections:</strong> Intermittent errors and seemingly random malfunctions can be caused by loose connections or dry joints in cabling.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Electrical and Motor-Related Problems</h3>
<p>Electrical issues affecting motors and their control can directly impact a robot's ability to move straight.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Motor Overload or Malfunction:</strong> Motors running with too high a torque, due to incorrect load data, excessive acceleration, or external forces, can lead to path deviations or even cause the robot to stop. Overloaded power semiconductors in drive units can also cause system halts.</li>
<li><strong>Encoder Issues:</strong> Faulty encoders or resolvers can result in incorrect feedback to the robot's control system, leading to inaccurate positioning and movement. Discrepancies in revolution counters or issues with serial measurement boards are indicators.</li>
<li><strong>Power Supply Problems:</strong> Insufficient or unstable power supply (e.g., mains voltage too high, incoming mains phase missing, DC link voltage issues) can cause motors to behave erratically or the system to halt.</li>
<li><strong>Intermittent Electrical Issues:</strong> External or internal interference, as well as thermal phenomena (e.g., major temperature changes), can cause intermittent electrical problems that affect robot operation.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Software and Control Issues</h3>
<p>Programming and control system errors can also cause a robot to deviate from a straight path.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Path Planning and Execution:</strong>
<ul>
<li><strong>Close Points and Speed:</strong> If programmed points are too close together, or if the robot attempts to move at very high speeds, the path may not be created correctly, or the system might slow down to compensate, affecting the intended straight line. Reducing speed or increasing the distance between points can help.</li>
<li><strong>Singularities:</strong> Operating too close to a singularity (a configuration where the robot loses degrees of freedom) can cause unpredictable movements and path errors. Modifying the path to avoid singularities or using joint interpolation may be necessary.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Incorrect Parameter Settings:</strong> Improperly configured tuning parameters, load data, or motion control settings can lead to inconsistent motion.</li>
<li><strong>System Overload:</strong> High CPU load or complex instructions can impact real-time motion control, causing deviations.</li>
</ul>
<h3>Specific Considerations for Mobile Robots (Not explicitly detailed in provided sources but common causes)</h3>
<p>For mobile robots, particularly those with differential drive systems, additional factors often contribute to non-straight movement:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Uneven Motor Power/Speed:</strong> Differences in the actual speed or torque delivered by each motor can cause the robot to pull to one side. This could be due to motor wear, varying voltage supply, or inconsistencies in motor controllers.</li>
<li><strong>Wheel Encoder Inaccuracies:</strong> Even small inaccuracies or drift in wheel encoder readings can lead to cumulative errors in odometry, causing the robot to veer off course over distance.</li>
<li><strong>Wheel Slippage:</strong> Uneven friction, loose wheels, or sudden acceleration/deceleration can cause one wheel to slip more than the other, resulting in a curved path. This is especially prevalent on certain floor surfaces.</li>
<li><strong>Chassis Misalignment:</strong> A physically misaligned chassis, where wheels are not perfectly parallel or perpendicular to the robot's intended direction of travel, will inherently cause the robot to drift.</li>
<li><strong>Uneven Weight Distribution:</strong> If the robot's weight is not evenly distributed, it can exert more pressure on one side, increasing friction and causing it to turn.</li>
<li><strong>Floor Surface Variations:</strong> Changes in the coefficient of friction across different floor materials (e.g., carpet to tile) can affect how the wheels grip and, consequently, the robot's ability to maintain a straight line.</li>
<li><strong>Control Loop Tuning:</strong> Poorly tuned PID (Proportional-Integral-Derivative) controllers for speed or position can result in oscillations or persistent errors that prevent straight-line motion.</li>
</ul>
