<p>A "reflash firmware failed" error indicates that the process of updating or reinstalling the internal software (firmware) on a device did not complete successfully. This can occur for a variety of reasons, often depending on the type of device and the specific flashing method being used.</p>
<p>Common causes for firmware reflash failures include:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Corrupt or Incorrect Firmware File</strong> The firmware file itself might be damaged, incomplete, or incompatible with your specific device model or hardware revision. It might also be the wrong type of file or fail an integrity check.</li>
<li><strong>Hardware/Software Incompatibility</strong> The firmware you're trying to flash may not be compatible with the existing hardware or software on your device. For instance, an older software version might not support a newer hardware unit.</li>
<li><strong>Communication Issues</strong> Problems with the connection between the device and the flashing tool can lead to failure. This could be due to damaged cables, loose connectors, or high levels of electromagnetic interference. Communication errors with specific components within the device can also halt the process.</li>
<li><strong>Interruption During Process</strong> If the power supply to the device or the computer performing the reflash is interrupted, or if the connection is lost during the flashing process, it can cause the reflash to fail.</li>
<li><strong>Driver or Software Problems</strong> The flashing software itself might be outdated, incorrectly installed, or experiencing internal errors, preventing it from properly communicating with the device.</li>
<li><strong>Internal Device Issues</strong> The device's internal memory or hardware might be corrupted or faulty, making it unable to accept new firmware.</li>
</ul>
<p>To troubleshoot this issue, you should:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Check for Specific Error Messages:</strong> Look for any detailed error codes or messages provided by the flashing software or on the device itself, as these can pinpoint the exact problem.</li>
<li><strong>Verify Firmware File Integrity and Compatibility:</strong> Ensure you have downloaded the correct firmware for your exact device model from a trusted source. If possible, re-download the file to rule out corruption.</li>
<li><strong>Inspect Connections:</strong> Double-check all cables (USB, Ethernet, etc.) for damage and ensure they are securely connected to both the device and the computer.</li>
<li><strong>Restart Everything:</strong> Reboot your computer and the device you are trying to reflash. Sometimes a simple restart can resolve temporary glitches.</li>
<li><strong>Use a Different Port/Cable:</strong> If possible, try connecting the device using a different USB port or cable.</li>
<li><strong>Temporarily Disable Antivirus/Firewall:</strong> Security software can sometimes interfere with flashing utilities. Temporarily disabling them might help, but remember to re-enable them afterward.</li>
<li><strong>Reinstall Flashing Software/Drivers:</strong> If the issue persists, try reinstalling the firmware flashing utility and any necessary device drivers on your computer.</li>
<li><strong>Ensure Stable Power:</strong> Make sure the device and the computer are connected to a stable power source and won't be accidentally disconnected during the process.</li>
</ol>
<p>If these steps do not resolve the issue, further investigation into the specific device and the exact error message would be necessary. In some cases, a failed reflash can "brick" a device, requiring professional repair or replacement of faulty hardware.</p>
<p><em>Source: ABB_IRC5_Operating_Troubleshooting_Manual</em></p>
