nsformer Connections:** Check that the transformer (A) dedicated to supplying the service outlet is correctly connected, with input and output voltages matching the specifications.",\n    "Page Number": "",\n    "URL": "projects/338431745290/locations/global/collections/default_collection/dataStores/linamar-vector-bootcamp/branches/0/documents/abb-irb8700-product-manual-pdf-p28"\n  },\n  {\n    "Document Name": "ABB_IRB8700_Product_Manual.pdf \\u2014 Page 27",\n    "Full Text": "If you\'re experiencing no voltage in the service outlet on your control module, several factors could be at play, primarily related to power supply and protective devices within the module itself. These service outlets typically provide 115/230 VAC.\\n\\nHere are the most probable causes and recommended actions to troubleshoot the issue:\\n\\n**Probable Causes:**\\n*   **Tripped Circuit Breaker (F5):** The most common reason for a lack of voltage is a tripped circuit breaker (F5) within the control module. This usually occurs if the equipment connected to the service outlet draws too much power.\\n*   **Tripped Earth Fault Protection (F4):** Similar to a tripped circuit breaker, the earth fault protection (F4) can trip if there\'s a current leakage to the ground from the connected equipment.\\n*   **Mains Power Supply Loss:** The control module itself might not be receiving adequate mains power, leading to no voltage at the service outlet.\\n*   **Incorrect Transformer Connection:** The transformer supplying the service outlet (Transformer A) might be incorrectly connected, meaning its input and output voltages aren\'t aligned with specifications.\\n\\n**Recommended Actions:**\\n1.  **Check the Circuit Breaker:** Verify that the circuit breaker (F5) in the control module has not tripped. If it has, reset it and ensure that any equipment you connect to the service outlet does not exceed its power rating to prevent future trips.\\n2.  **Inspect Earth Fault Protection:** Confirm that the earth