    "excerpt": "### General Safety Precautions for Troubleshooting:\n\n*   **Qualified Personnel Only:** Only qualified personnel familiar with the entire robot installation, its specific risks, and relevant safety regulations should perform troubleshooting and corrective maintenance. Troubleshooting on a powered-on controller should specifically be performed by personnel trained by the manufacturer or their field engineers.\n*   **Risk Assessment:** A thorough risk assessment must be conducted to identify and address both general and robot-system-specific hazards before commencing any troubleshooting work.\n*   **Anticipate Movement:** Always assume the robot manipulator can move unexpectedly at any time, especially when power is on or safety circuits might be bypassed.\n*   **Understand System State:** Be aware that during troubleshooting, power may be switched on, and the manipulator might be controlled manually or by a running program. Safety circuits might also be temporarily muted or disconnected, meaning the system may not behave as it normally would under safe operating conditions.\n*   **Brake Integrity:** If holding brakes are suspected to be non-operational, secure the robot arm system by other means before working on it. Never stand beneath a robot's axes if the holding brakes are disabled or faulty, as a collapsing arm can cause severe injury or death. Regular brake testing is recommended as part of maintenance.\n*   **Environmental Awareness:** Be mindful of the entire working environment and any potential extraordinary risks that might arise from an interrupted working process.",
