    "excerpt": "### Lockout/Tagout (LOTO) Procedures:\n\nWhile troubleshooting may sometimes require power to be on, general repair and maintenance work should follow strict Lockout/Tagout (LOTO) principles:\n\n*   **De-energize and Isolate:** For repairs, disconnect the main power supply to the robot by setting the main switch to OFF.\n*   **Secure from Reconnection:** The main supply should be connected so that it can be turned off from outside the robot's working space. Always lock the main switch on the controller cabinet with a safety lock to prevent accidental re-energization while working on the system.\n*   **Verify Zero Energy State:** Ensure all electrical, pneumatic, and hydraulic power is switched off before performing service work. Be aware of stored electrical energy in components like the DC link or ultracapacitor bank units, even when the main power is off. Units like I/O modules can also be supplied with external power.\n*   **Release Stored Energy (Pneumatic/Hydraulic):** For pneumatic and hydraulic systems, clearly visible drain facilities should be used to release pressure before any adjustments or maintenance. All pressure in the complete system must be released before repairs, and work on hydraulic equipment should only be performed by personnel with specialized knowledge. Use dump valves and shot bolts to prevent gravity-related hazards.",
