<h3 style="font-family: sans-serif;">ABB_IRC5_Operating_Troubleshooting_Manual</h3>
<p style="font-family: sans-serif;">Robot brake safety is a critical aspect of industrial robotics, encompassing design, maintenance, and operational protocols to prevent accidents and ensure the reliable functioning of robotic systems. Industrial robots are equipped with holding brakes, which are essential safety components, particularly for larger models where the heavy robot arm can pose a lethal hazard if the brakes are non-operational.</p>
<p style="font-family: sans-serif;">Key aspects of robot brake safety include:</p>
<ul style="font-family: sans-serif;">
<li><strong>Holding Brakes and their Importance</strong> The holding brakes on each robot axis are crucial for maintaining the robot's position, especially when power is removed or during static holds. A faulty, worn, or disconnected holding brake can lead to unexpected and dangerous movements, potentially causing serious injury or damage.</li>
<li><strong>Brake Testing</strong> Regular testing of holding brakes is necessary because they wear down during operation. To test a brake's function, each axis should be moved to a position where the combined weight of the manipulator and any load creates a maximum static load. The motors are then switched off, and the axis is inspected to ensure it maintains its position. If the manipulator does not move, the brake function is considered adequate. Many robot systems recommend using specific service routines like "BrakeCheck" or "Cyclic Brake Check" as part of regular maintenance.</li>
<li><strong>Emergency Release Procedures</strong> In emergencies, robot axis brakes can be manually released using a brake release button. However, this action carries significant risks, as the robot axes can move quickly and unexpectedly. Before releasing brakes, it is crucial to ensure no personnel are near or beneath the robot and to consider the manipulator's weight to prevent additional hazards.</li>
<li><strong>Hazards During Maintenance and Troubleshooting</strong> Special precautions are required when performing maintenance or troubleshooting with power switched on, as safety circuits may be disengaged, and the manipulator could move unexpectedly. A jammed brake release button can also inadvertently release a motor brake when power is applied, potentially causing severe injury or damage.</li>
<li><strong>Safety Standards and Regulations</strong> Industrial robots are designed and integrated according to various international and regional safety standards. These include:
<ul>
<li><strong>ISO 10218-1:</strong> Robots for industrial environments – Safety requirements – Part 1: Robots.</li>
<li><strong>ISO 13849-1:</strong> Safety of machinery – Safety related parts of control systems – Part 1: General principles for design.</li>
<li><strong>IEC 60204-1:</strong> Safety of machinery – Electrical equipment of machines – Part 1: General requirements.</li>
<li><strong>ANSI/RIA R15.06:</strong> Safety Requirements for Industrial Robots and Robot Systems (North America).</li>
<li><strong>CAN/CSA Z434:</strong> Industrial Robots and Robot Systems – General Safety Requirements (Canada).</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p style="font-family: sans-serif;">The robot system integrator is responsible for conducting a thorough risk assessment and ensuring that the robot system's design and installation comply with all applicable national and regional safety standards and regulations.</p>
</div>
</details>Consumed 34 orchestrator stream event(s).
