ed simultaneously.\\n3.  **Release the Brake:** Press the corresponding button on the internal brake release unit for the specific robot axis you wish to release. The buttons are numbered according to the axes.\\n4.  **Re-engage the Brake:** The brake will re-engage as soon as you release the button.\\n\\nIt\'s also mentioned that a 24 VDC power supply can be used to release brakes on specific axes during repair or maintenance, such as for axis-2, axis-3, or axis-6. For example, to release brakes on axis-3, you would connect 24V to pin 2 and 0V to pin 5 of connector R2.MP3.",\n    "Page Number": "",\n    "URL": "projects/338431745290/locations/global/collections/default_collection/dataStores/linamar-vector-bootcamp/branches/0/documents/abb-irb8700-product-manual-pdf-p85"\n  },\n  {\n    "Document Name": "ABB_IRB8700_Product_Manual.pdf \\u2014 Page 86",\n    "Full Text": "To manually release the brakes on an ABB IRB 8700 robot, follow these steps, keeping in mind the critical safety precautions involved. The process involves using the internal brake release unit, which has individual buttons for each axis.\\n\\n**Safety First:**\\n*   **DANGER:** When releasing the holding brakes, the robot axes may move very quickly and unexpectedly. Ensure no personnel are near or beneath the robot arm.\\n*   For larger robot models like the IRB 8700, manual movement may require an overhead crane or similar equipment.\\n*   Before releasing brakes, confirm that the weight of the robot\'s arms will not increase pressure on any trapped individuals, which could worsen injuries.\\n*   If performing service work, ensure the power is turned off.\\n*   After service work involving the brake release unit, verify that the push-buttons are not jammed by pressing them individually. A jammed button with power on will release the affected motor brake and can cause serious injury or damage.\\n\\n**Procedure for Manual Brake Release:**\\n\\n1.  **Locate the Internal Brake Release Unit:** The inte