    "excerpt": "Servicing the ABB IRB 8700 robot requires strict adherence to safety protocols to prevent injury and equipment damage. Key precautions encompass personnel qualifications, lockout/tagout procedures, personal protective equipment, awareness of potential hazards, and specific steps for various service activities.\n\n**1. Qualified Personnel and Training:**\nOnly individuals who are thoroughly trained on the robot's operation, handling, installation, and maintenance, and are familiar with associated safety matters, are permitted to service the IRB 8700. It is crucial that personnel are not under the influence of alcohol, drugs, or other intoxicating substances. Corrective maintenance must be performed by qualified personnel familiar with the entire installation and its specific risks.\n\n**2. Lockout/Tagout (Energy Isolation):**\nBefore entering the robot's working area or performing any service, installation, or repair work, all electric power, hydraulic pressure, and air pressure supplies to the robot must be turned off. A critical safety measure is to always lock the main switch on the controller cabinet with a safety lock to prevent unauthorized power-on while work is in progress. If the IRB 8700 is connected to power, it must always be connected to protective earth before any maintenance work begins.\n\n**3. Personal Protective Equipment (PPE):**\nAlways use appropriate personal protective equipment based on a risk assessment for the specific robot installation.\n\n**4. General Safety Risks and Precautions:**\n*   **Moving Robots:** Moving robots are potentially lethal. Always establish safety zones that must be crossed before admittance to the robot's working space, using devices like light beams or sensitive mats.\n*   **Stored Energy:** Be aware of stored energy within the robot's counterbalancing systems, which can be released during dismantling. The controller also stores heat and electrical energy (e.g., DC link, Ultracapacitor bank unit).\n*   **Gravity:** Robot axes are affected by gravity when brakes are released. There is a risk of being crushed by moving parts, including the parallel arm if present. Gravity can also cause parts or objects held by pneumatic/hydraulic systems to drop; dump valves and shot bolts should be used to prevent this.\n*   **Falling Objects:** When assembling or dismantling mechanical units, watch out for falling objects.\n*   **Slipping/Falling:** Never use the robot as a ladder or climb on its motors or other parts during service work, due to high temperatures and potential oil spills.\n*   **Collision Risks:** When programming robot movements, identify potential collision risks before the first test run.\n*   **Emergency Stops:** Emergency stop buttons must be easily accessible to quickly stop the robot.\n*   **Working Inside the Robot's Range:** When working inside the robot's operating range, always put a safety lock on the cell door and carry the three-position enabling device to prevent others from taking control. Never stay beneath the robot's axes, as unexpected movement can occur.\n\n**5. First Test Run After Service:**\nAfter repair, installation, or maintenance involving disassembly, several safety risks must be considered before the first test run. Follow this procedure:\n1.  Remove all service tools and foreign objects from the robot and its working area.\n2.  Verify the robot is secured to its position.\n3.  Ensure any safety equipment used to secure or restrict the robot arm during service is removed.\n4.  Verify that fixtures and workpieces are well secured.\n5.  Properly install all safety equipment.\n6.  Ensure all personnel are at a safe distance, outside the robot's reach and behind safety fences.\n7.  Pay special attention to the function of the serviced part.\n\n**6. Specific Hazards:**\n*   **Jammed Brake Release Buttons:** After service work inside the SMB recess involving the brake release unit, the push-buttons may become jammed. If power is turned on while a button is jammed, the affected motor brake will be released, potentially causing severe injury and damage. Always verify that brake release buttons are working freely after such service by pressing them one by one with the power off. Adjust alignment if a button jams.\n*   **Pneumatic/Hydraulic Systems:** Special safety regulations apply. Components that remain pressurized after shutdown must have visible drain facilities and warning signs. Release all pressure in these systems before repairs. Only personnel with specialized knowledge should work on hydraulic equipment. Regularly inspect pipes, hoses, and connections for leaks and damage, and repair them immediately, as splashed oil can cause injury or fire.\n\n**7. Cleaning:**\nBefore cleaning, turn off all electrical power supplies to the manipulator before entering its workspace. Always verify the robot's protection type. Never point water jets at connectors, joints, sealings, or gaskets, and do not use compressed air or unapproved solvents. Do not spray closer than 0.4 meters or remove protective covers before cleaning. Always ensure all protective covers are fitted before cleaning.\n\nBy adhering to these safety precautions and consulting the ABB IRB 8700 product manual for detailed procedures, the risks associated with servicing the robot can be significantly mitigated."
  }
]
