<p>A motor phase short circuit is an electrical fault where an unintended low-resistance path is created between different phases of a motor or motor cable, or between a phase and the ground. This condition prevents normal operation of the motor.</p>
<p><strong>Causes of a Motor Phase Short Circuit:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Cable and Connector Issues</strong> Short circuits can occur directly within the motor cables or connectors, either between phases or from a phase to ground.</li>
<li><strong>Motor Internal Faults</strong> The motor itself can develop a short circuit, often due to a failure in its windings, either between different windings or between a winding and the motor's casing (ground).</li>
<li><strong>Contamination</strong> The presence of dust, metal fragments, or other contaminants in the contactors of the cables or within the motor windings can bridge electrical connections, leading to a short circuit.</li>
<li><strong>Faulty Components</strong> A defective motor or motor cable is a common cause.</li>
<li><strong>Improper Connection or Configuration</strong> If the motor is not correctly connected to its drive unit, or if the motor's configuration data is inaccurate, it can contribute to a short circuit condition.</li>
<li><strong>Operational Stress</strong> Excessive axis load, a stalled motor (possibly from a collision), or an oversized motor for the drive unit can also induce short circuits. High motor current or low DC link voltage can also be probable causes.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Consequences and Symptoms:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>The motor will cease to operate, and the system will enter a "Motors Off" state with zero torque, or a "SYS HALT" state.</li>
<li>A "Motor Phase Short Circuit Warning" may initially appear, indicating a brief short circuit. If this warning does not persist, it might not require immediate intervention.</li>
<li>Other symptoms may include a critical drive unit error, potentially related to over-temperature, high drive transistor current, or excessive motor current.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Troubleshooting and Recommended Actions:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Inspect and Replace Components</strong> Thoroughly check and replace any faulty cables, connectors, or the motor itself. Ensure motor cables are correctly connected to the drive unit.</li>
<li><strong>Resistance Measurement</strong> Disconnect power and measure the resistance of both the motor and its cables to identify internal short circuits or shorts to ground. Verify that motor cables have no internal short circuits or shorts to ground.</li>
<li><strong>Cleanliness</strong> Remove any contamination, such as dust or metal fragments, from contactors and motor windings.</li>
<li><strong>Configuration Verification</strong> Confirm that the motor data in the configuration file is accurate and matches the installed motor.</li>
<li><strong>System Checks</strong> Review the event logs for other hardware error messages. Verify that the incoming mains voltage is within specified limits.</li>
<li><strong>Operational Adjustments</strong> If the problem is related to operational stress, reduce the speed of the user program, rewrite it to minimize hard braking or deceleration, or ensure the axis load is not excessively high. Also, check that the maximum motor current is appropriate for the drive unit.</li>
</ul>
</details>Consumed 42 orchestrator stream event(s).
